[{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/authors.html","id":null,"dir":"","previous_headings":"","what":"Authors","title":"Authors and Citation","text":"Krystyna Grzesiak. Author, maintainer. Jeffrey Näf. Author.","code":""},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/authors.html","id":"citation","dir":"","previous_headings":"","what":"Citation","title":"Authors and Citation","text":"Grzesiak K, Näf J (2026). miceDRF: Imputation 'mice' Distributional Random Forests. R package version 0.1.0, https://github.com/KrystynaGrzesiak/miceDRF.","code":"@Manual{,   title = {miceDRF: Imputation with 'mice' and Distributional Random Forests},   author = {Krystyna Grzesiak and Jeffrey Näf},   year = {2026},   note = {R package version 0.1.0},   url = {https://github.com/KrystynaGrzesiak/miceDRF}, }"},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/index.html","id":"micedrf-imputation-with-distributional-random-forests-in-mice","dir":"","previous_headings":"","what":"Imputation with mice and Distributional Random Forests","title":"Imputation with mice and Distributional Random Forests","text":"miceDRF provides imputation method mice framework based distributional random forests (DRF). package extends multiple imputation chained equations (MICE) nonparametric approach models conditional distributions rather conditional means. allows flexible imputation complex data structures, nonlinear effects, heterogeneous conditional distributions. method can used directly within standard mice workflow via:","code":"method = \"DRF\""},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/index.html","id":"installation","dir":"","previous_headings":"","what":"Installation","title":"Imputation with mice and Distributional Random Forests","text":"miceDRF package can intstalled CRAN: install development version run:","code":"install.packages(\"miceDRF\") if (!requireNamespace(\"devtools\", quietly = TRUE)) {   install.packages(\"devtools\") }  devtools::install_github(\"KrystynaGrzesiak/miceDRF\")"},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/index.html","id":"example","dir":"","previous_headings":"","what":"Example","title":"Imputation with mice and Distributional Random Forests","text":"","code":"library(mice) library(miceDRF)  set.seed(123)  # Generate data n <- 200 d <- 5  X <- matrix(runif(n * d), nrow = n, ncol = d)  # Introduce missing values pmiss <- 0.2  X.NA <- apply(X, 2, function(x) {   U <- runif(length(x))   ifelse(U <= pmiss, NA, x) })  # Imputation with DRF imp <- mice(X.NA, m = 1, method = \"DRF\")  Ximp <- complete(imp)"},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/index.html","id":"references","dir":"","previous_headings":"","what":"References","title":"Imputation with mice and Distributional Random Forests","text":"Näf, J., Scornet, E., & Josse, J. (2024). good imputation MAR missingness? arXiv preprint. https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.19196 Cevid, D., Michel, L., Näf, J., Meinshausen, N., Buehlmann, P. (2022). Distributional random forests: Heterogeneity adjustment multivariate distributional regression. Journal Machine Learning Research, 23(333), 1–79.","code":""},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/index.html","id":"citation","dir":"","previous_headings":"","what":"Citation","title":"Imputation with mice and Distributional Random Forests","text":"use miceDRF research, please cite: Jeffrey Näf, Erwan Scornet, Julie Josse (2026). Good Imputation MAR Missingness? arXiv preprint arXiv:2403.19196. https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.19196","code":""},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/reference/mice.impute.DRF.html","id":null,"dir":"Reference","previous_headings":"","what":"Imputation with Distributional Random Forests for 'mice' — mice.impute.DRF","title":"Imputation with Distributional Random Forests for 'mice' — mice.impute.DRF","text":"Imputes missing values using distributional random forests within multiple imputation chained equations framework implemented mice package.","code":""},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/reference/mice.impute.DRF.html","id":"ref-usage","dir":"Reference","previous_headings":"","what":"Usage","title":"Imputation with Distributional Random Forests for 'mice' — mice.impute.DRF","text":"","code":"mice.impute.DRF(   y,   ry,   x,   wy = NULL,   min.node.size = 1,   num.features = 10,   num.trees = 10,   ... )"},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/reference/mice.impute.DRF.html","id":"arguments","dir":"Reference","previous_headings":"","what":"Arguments","title":"Imputation with Distributional Random Forests for 'mice' — mice.impute.DRF","text":"y Vector imputed. ry Logical vector indicating elements y observed used fit imputation model. x Numeric design matrix length(y) rows, containing predictors y. matrix contain missing values. wy Logical vector indicating elements y imputations generated. NULL, defaults !ry. min.node.size Target minimum number observations tree leaf distributional random forest. Default 1. num.features Number random features sample split. Default 10. num.trees Number trees distributional random forest. Default 10. ... Additional arguments passed mice compatibility mice.impute interface. Currently ignored.","code":""},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/reference/mice.impute.DRF.html","id":"value","dir":"Reference","previous_headings":"","what":"Value","title":"Imputation with Distributional Random Forests for 'mice' — mice.impute.DRF","text":"numeric vector imputed values entries y indicated wy. vector length sum(wy) returned mice replace missing values current variable.","code":""},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/reference/mice.impute.DRF.html","id":"details","dir":"Reference","previous_headings":"","what":"Details","title":"Imputation with Distributional Random Forests for 'mice' — mice.impute.DRF","text":"function called internally mice imputation method set \"DRF\". variable missing values, distributional random forest fitted observed values using remaining variables predictors. Missing values imputed sampling observed responses according forest weights.","code":""},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/reference/mice.impute.DRF.html","id":"references","dir":"Reference","previous_headings":"","what":"References","title":"Imputation with Distributional Random Forests for 'mice' — mice.impute.DRF","text":"Näf, J., Scornet, E., Josse, J. (2024). \"good imputation MAR missingness?\" https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.19196. Cevid, D., Michel, L., Näf, J., Meinshausen, N., Buehlmann, P. (2022). \"Distributional random forests: Heterogeneity adjustment multivariate distributional regression.\" Journal Machine Learning Research, 23(333), 1–79.","code":""},{"path":"https://krystynagrzesiak.github.io/miceDRF/reference/mice.impute.DRF.html","id":"ref-examples","dir":"Reference","previous_headings":"","what":"Examples","title":"Imputation with Distributional Random Forests for 'mice' — mice.impute.DRF","text":"","code":"library(mice) #>  #> Attaching package: ‘mice’ #> The following object is masked from ‘package:stats’: #>  #>     filter #> The following objects are masked from ‘package:base’: #>  #>     cbind, rbind  set.seed(123) X <- matrix(rnorm(1000), nrow = 100) X[runif(length(X)) < 0.3] <- NA  imp <- mice(X, method = \"DRF\", m = 1, maxit = 1, printFlag = FALSE) complete(imp) #>              V1          V2          V3          V4          V5          V6 #> 1   -1.13813694 -0.71040656  2.19881035 -0.71524219 -0.07355602 -0.60189285 #> 2    0.89512566  0.25688371  1.31241298 -0.75268897 -1.16865142 -0.99369859 #> 3   -1.12310858 -0.24669188 -0.26514506 -1.99274849  0.12631586  1.02678506 #> 4    0.07050839 -0.34754260  0.02098359 -1.05251328 -0.02884155  0.75106130 #> 5    0.12928774 -0.95161857 -0.56187636 -0.43715953  0.67069597 -1.50916654 #> 6    1.71506499 -0.04502772 -0.47624689  0.65119328 -1.65054654 -0.09514745 #> 7    0.46091621 -0.38022652 -0.26565163 -2.01421050 -0.53880